text: Accadacca: ACDC, Australian Hard Rock band
Aerial ping pong: Australian Rules Football, Victorians usually dont like this
Argy Bargy: A fight, usually push and shove
Aussie salute: Waving away the flies
B&S ball band: A band that plays at Bachelor and Spinster Balls, an outback tradition
Back of Bourke: Very remote place
Backhander: A bribe or an under-the-table payment
Bag: To Criticize, Claim something, Large amount
Bail: To cancel plans or leave abruptly
Ball and chain: A humorous or mildly sarcastic term for a spouse, typically referring to a wife
Banjo Country: A very rural or remote area.
Banter: Playfully exchange teasing remarks between friends
Barra: Short for Barramundi, a popular Australian fish.
Barrack: Cheer someone or team on
Barry Crocker: A shocker, a really bad experience, or a big mistake
Basket case: A person or situation that is completely out of control, failing, or in a bad state
Beak: Nose, can also mean a Court Judge
Beat around the bush: Someone who says a lot without saying anything,
Beauty: An expression of approval or excitement
Beer Goggles: The effect of alcohol making someone appear more attractive than they actually are.
Beer gut: A large belly, often associated with drinking too much beer.
Belly Full: Full of alcohol, meaning drunk
Beyond the black stump: See Back of Bourke
Bible basher: An individual with strong religious convictions who delivers sermons.
Big note oneself: To brag or talk oneself up, often to appear more important.
Big Smoke: A large city thats often polluted
Big Unit: A large or physically strong person, usually male.
Billabong: A pond or waterhole in a dry riverbed
Billy: A teapot or container used to boil water over a fire
Bin Chicken: Australian white ibis, a bird commonly found scavenging in bins.
Bingle: A minor motor vehicle accident
Bit of a yarn: To have a talk or chat with someone, storytelling
Bities: Biting insects like ants, or mosquitoes
Blind Freddy: To point out something obvious, Even Blind Freddy could have seen that
Blow: A single pass of the shears over the sheep
Blow in: An uninvited person or temporary visitor
Blow in the bag: An alcohol breathalyzer test conducted by the police
Blow me down: An expression of astonishment or surprise
Blowie: A large blowfly, common in Australia
Blowies: Small fish or blowflies (depends on context).
Blunnies: Blundstone boots, popular Australian work boots.
Boardies: Board shorts, worn by surfers
Bobby: Glass of beer in Western Australia but this term is not widely recognized outside of WA.
Bodgy: Something that is of inferior quality
Bodgy Job: A poorly done or dodgy repair.
Bog in: Eating food, usually quickly or with enthusiasm
Bogged: Stuck in deep sand or mud in your car
Bogus: Fake, false, or not genuine.
Boil Over: An unexpected sporting upset.
Bomb: An old and unreliable car
Bombed: High on drugs or failed badly
Bondi Cigar: A piece of poo floating at Australias most famous beach, Bondi. Also referred to as ËœBrown Eyed Mullet
Bonnet: The hood of a car
Boof head: A fool or a thickheaded person.
Boogie board: A small surfboard used for bodyboarding
Boot: The trunk of a car
Booze bus: A police vehicle used for roadside breath testing.
Booze Hound: Someone who loves drinking alcohol.
Brass razoo: Money, usually used to indicate lack of,  i.e. I havent got a brass razoo
Break: An area where waves break, often used for surfing
Brick shithouse: Something that is very solid or very well built, i.e. He is built like a brick shithouse
Bring a plate: Bring some food to share
Buckleys chance: No chance, Buckleys or none
Budgie smugglers: Tight fitting swimming trunks for males
Buggerlugs: A term of endearment for someone you want to annoy
Bullshit: A lie, or total crap
Bullshit artist: Someone who bullshits a lot
Bum fluff: Light facial hair on males just starting to shave
Bunghole: A crude or humorous term for the anus.
Bunyip: A mythical Australian creature that lurks in billabongs and swamps.
Bush band: A folk music group that plays traditional Australian songs
Bush Bash: Driving through the bushland or having a bush party.
Bush telly: A campfire, often used as the main entertainment while camping
Busted: Broken, also means caught in the act
Butcher: A small glass of beer. Normally only in South Australia
BYO: Bring Your Own, usually alcohol but can be anything
Cabbie: A cab driver, or taxi driver
Call it a day: To stop
Camel: A person who drinks very little water but a lot of beer/alcohol
Camp oven: A cast-iron pot used for cooking over an open fire
Cane Cutter: A worker who cuts sugarcane (Queensland origin).
Cark it: Die or break down
Cats pajamas: Something stylish, fashionable, or impressive.
Checkout chick: A supermarket cashier or clerk
Cheeky: Someone who shows a lack of politeness in a likeable way
Chewie: A piece of chewing gum
Chewing the fat: Having a talk
Chick flick: A movie that women like. Usually romantic, comedies, etc.
China Plate: Rhyming slang for Mate
Chisel: Short for Cold Chisel, an iconic Aussie rock band
Chrisse: Chrissie or Chrissy means Christmas
Chuck a lefty: Please turn left
Chuck a righty: Please turn right
Chuck a sickie: Pretend to be sick to skip work
Chuck a Uey: Do a U turn
Chuck a wobbly: Throwing a big tantrum
Chunder: Vomit when youre really, really drunk
Chunder overboard: To vomit over the side of a boat, often from seasickness
Clanger: A big mistake or error.
Claytons: Something that is fake or not genuine
Clucky: Feeling maternal, i.e. Shes gone all clucky
Coat hanger: Nickname for the Sydney Harbor Bridge
Cockie: A cockatoo, a native Australian bird. Also the boss on a property or farm
Cods Wallop: Old-fashioned slang for total rubbish or nonsense. Rarely used in Australia but still understood
Come a buster: Made a big mistake
Couldnt be bothered: Dont want to do something
Crack onto someone: To pursue someone romantically
Cranky: In a really foul mood!
Crawler: A person who attempts to ingratiate themselves with others in an insincere manner.
Creamed: To achieve a decisive victory over the opposing team.
Crook: Feeling unwell or a criminal.
Cross country wrestling: A humorous way to describe rugby league, referring to its physical tackles and aggressive gameplay.
Crow Eater: Someone from South Australia
Crutching: Removing wool from around the sheeps rear and legs
Cry baby: An adult who easily becomes upset
Cut someones grass: To hit on or pursue someone elses partner
Dad n Dave: Rhyming slang for a shave. Dad n Dave was a well-known radio show.
Damper: Simple bread usually cooked on a camp fire
Darwin Stubbie: The world's largest beer bottle holds 2.25 litres and comes from the Northern Territory.
Dawn Service: A commemorative ceremony held at dawn on Anzac Day, April 25th
Dazzler: An exceptionally good looking person
Dead Horse: Rhyming slang for tomato sauce
Dead marine: An empty beer bottle
Dead Ringer: Exactly the same, or an exact copy.
Death Sticks: Cigarettes, Or Cancer Stick
Death trap: An extremely dangerous and unroadworthy car
Deep and Meaningful: An important, personal conversation you have with someone. Also known as D & M
Didg: Short for didgeridoo, a traditional Aboriginal instrument
Didgeridoo: Aboriginal wind instrument made from hollowed tree trunk
Divvy van: Police wagon where you are transported back to the police station
Dodgy: Not quite right, or a shady character.  Unreliable, suspicious, or of poor quality.
Dog And Bone: Rhyming Slang For Phone
Dogs Eye: Rhyming slang for meat pie
Dole: Unemployment payments from the Australian government
Done a Steve Bradbury: Fortunate to win something.
Done like a dinner: Completely outwitted or defeated
Donkey Vote: Voters who merely number the candidates in the order they are listed on the ballot paper (without regard for the merits of the candidates)
Donkeys Years: An exceptionally long time!
Drink with the flies: To drink alcohol by yourself
Drop bear: An imaginary animal resembling a koala, featuring sharp jaws and teeth, which is humorously said to eat tourists.
Dummy: A pacifier for a baby
Dunny roll wave: A small, weak wave that fizzles out quickly
Dunny Run: A trip to the outdoor toilet (common in outback Australia).
Durrey: A cigarette you roll yourself
Earbasher: Someone who talks nonstop to you
Easy Campese: Its really easy. David Campese used to be an Australian rugby player
Easy on: Slow down or calm down
Esky: A container that keeps food and drinks cool.
Even Stevens: Where you dont owe each other anything
Fair go mate: It means you want to be treated fairly
Fair Whack: A fair deal or fair share of something.
Festy: Something that smells off or is decomposing
Fish o: The fish and chip shop
Flat chat: Doing something very quickly
Flick: To get rid of something
Flick it on: To turn something on, like a television (Idiot Box) or radio
Flogging the plastic: Using your credit card a lot usually unsustainably
Foodie: A person who loves gourmet food
Footy: Australian rules football or rugby
Fossick: To search or rummage for something, often used in reference to looking for gold or valuables
Front up: To turn up somewhere
Frostie: A very cold bottle of beer
Fugly: A mesh of f@#king and ugly
Full as a goog: Very full
Furphy: A rumor or tall story
Furphy Tank: A water cart, originally used to spread gossip among soldiers.
Gabba: The Brisbane Cricket Ground. Located in the Brisbane suburb of Woolloongabba
Galah: A native Australian bird, but the slang version means a person is a noisy idiot
Gander: Take a look at something
Garbos: The garbage people who collect your rubbish
Get a Guernsey: To receive an award
Get a wiggle on: I need to keep moving
Get on your goat: Youre annoying me
Get your hand off it!: Stop talking crap
Gibber: A rocky desert area, common in outback Australia.
Ginger Beer: Rhyming slang for Engineer
Give it a burl: Try it
Give it a crack: If youre giving something a crack, that means youre having a go.
Give it away: To give up
Goanna: Rhyming slang for a piano
Gone walkabout: Disappeared, left to go somewhere. Comes from Aboriginal Australian culture, referring to traditional journeys, but often used casually today.
Good oil: Useful information, or just something that is particularly good in general
Goon: This is what Australians call cheap boxed wine.
Goon bag: Wine that comes from the silver bladder in boxed wine
Granny flat: Small apartment for elderly parents
Grog: Alcohol beer, wine, anything alcoholic!
Gun Shearer: A highly skilled and fast shearer
Hangry: Hungry and angry at the same time
Have a Blue: To have a fight
Have a Captain Cook: Have a look
Have a crack: Give it a go
Have a go you mug: Youre not trying
Have a lash at it: To have a try at something
High as a kite: High on drugs
Hit the frog and toad: Going for a drive on the road
Hit the sack: Go to bed
Hooley Dooley: An expression when youre surprised
Hospital pass: A pass you receive in football that might land you in a hospital ward because youre tackled heavily
Hot under the collar: Someone who is angry
How are ya mate?: How are you?
I smell bacon: I know that the traffic police are around
Jesus Bars: Those handles located in the car ceiling that you hang on to when youre having a wild ride. Why? Because people often say "Jesus!" when grabbing them.
Jug: Electric kettle. In some countries, "jug" means a large beer pitcher instead.
Junk Food: Fast food thats very unhealthy
King Brown: A 750 ml bottle of beer
Knackered: Very tired. It also means when testicles are removed from one of your pets
Larrikin: A mischievous but good-hearted person
Lemon: Something completely useless. Commonly referred to bad cars
Lift: Either a ride in a car, or an elevator
Like a rat up a drain pipe: Doing something very quickly
Liquid lunch: Having only beer for lunch
Little Aussie Battler: Someone who is experiencing extreme hardship
Loaded: You have a lot of money
Lob: To drop by or arrive unexpectedly
Lolly water: Soft drink, or a fizzy drink like soda
Longneck: A 750 ml bottle of beer
Look see: To have a look at something
Loose cannon: Someone who is completely out of control
Mad as a Cut snake: This phrase is a distinctly Australian manner of indicating that someone is truly angry.
Mallee Root: A tough, gnarled piece of wood from the Mallee tree.
Mates rates: Discounted services, usually for friends
Metho: Methylated spirits, or pure alcohol
Middy: A 285 ml glass of beer in New South Wales
Milk bar: Somewhere you can buy a milkshake
Munchies: Snacks like chips, pies, chocolate bars.
Munted: Broken or ruined; can also mean intoxicated.
Mystery meat: Processed meat goods where youre not quite sure whats in them,
Nauty: A playful Aussie slang twist on nautical
Newbie: The new person at work
Nigel: Someone who has no friends. Used in the context of Nigel No Friends
No hoper: Someone who will never ever do well in life
Noughts and crosses: Tic tac toe
Nut out: To work something out
Off your head: You are on drugs and they are making you act out of character
Old mate: Someone whose name you forgot
On the grog: Drinking lots of alcohol, or having a session
One armed bandit: A slot machine/poker machine
One for the road: The last drink at the pub before you go home
One off: Something that is one of a kind or unique
Ordinary: It can mean excellent, or mediocre.
Oxygen thief: Someone you do not like who really doesnt deserve to be using up all of the earths resources
Pack shit: To be very scared
Passion Pop: Cheap, fizzy alcoholic drink
Petrol head: Someone who loves cars
Pick the eyes out of it: To choose the best bits
Piffed: Thrown away into the bin
Pig out: Eating lots of food
Piker: Someone who leaves your party or night out early
Pink slip: What you get if you lose your job
Pint: A large glass of beer, usually 500 ml
Play funny buggers: To act in a silly way
Plays is straight: Someone who is fair
Pommy Shower: Not actually using a shower with water just rubbing deodorant on yourself
Pot: A 285 ml glass of beer
Pozzy: A good position or advantage
Pub crawl: Going to a lot of places to drink in one night
Pull a swiftie: Do something dishonest
Pull your head in: Shut up, or mind your own business
Put a sock in it: Shut up
Put on the wobbly boot: To get drunk
Gutted: Feeling deeply disappointed or heartbroken
Raffertys Rules: No rules at all
Rat bag: Cheeky person or idiot
Ringer: The fastest shearer in the shed
Rip: A strong current that can pull swimmers out to sea
Rip off: Something that is a lot more expensive than it should be
Road train: A large truck with multiple trailers
Roadie: A beer you have on the way home from somewhere
Rock up: To rock up is to arrive.
Rollie: A cigarette youve rolled up yourself
Roo bar: Bull bar on a car
Ropeable: Someone who is incredibly angry
Rumpus room: A recreation or family room
Saltbush: A hardy native Australian plant that thrives in the outback.
Sand Groper: Someone from Western Australia
Sanger bag: A lunchbox or sandwich bag
Scarce as hens teeth: Very rare
Schooner: A 425 ml glass of beer
Screamer: Someone who becomes drunk on not much alcohol
See a man about a dog: Go and take a pee
Shark biscuit: A surfer thats just starting out
Shell be apples: It will be all good
Shell be right!: It will be okay
Shit box: A very old car
Shit house: Something thats really bad or poor quality. It also means toilet
Shit kicker: Someone who does an unpleasant job no one else wants to do
Shocker: Something really bad or poor quality
Shorey: A small wave that breaks close to the shore, often dumping surfers
Shout: Buy something for someone, usually drink but can be food or any other item
Show pony: Someone who likes showing off a lot, such as man dressing up to try and impress everyone by behaving like a peacock
Show the ropes: Show how things work around here
Sickie: A sick day off work
Silly season: Christmas and New Year period
Sit on a beer: To drink a beer slowly
Six pack: A pack of six bottles of beer
Skimpy: Light on clothes, food serving, etc.
Skite: To brag or boast about something
Skull: To drink a beer very fast
Snag bag: Sausage roll (mystery meat encased in pastry)
Sook: Someone who complains a lot
Speedo: The speedometer on a car
Spill your guts: To reveal a deep down secret
Spit the dummy: To have a tantrum or react angrily.
Spread: A large collection of different types of food
Spruiker: Someone whos trying to sell you something
Spunk: A really good looking person
Stiffy: When a man has an erection
Straight up and down: An honest person
Straya Rock: A term for Australian pub rock music
Strewth: An expression of surprise or shock.
Strike a blow: To help with something
Stroppy: Someone who is in an irritable mood.
Stubbie: A 375 ml bottle of beer
Sucked in: To be tricked into something
Sundowner: A beer drunk at sunset
Surfies: People who surf all of the time
Sus it out: To investigate something
Swifie: To trick someone, i.e., Pull a swiftie
Tall Tale: Exagertated or false story
Tallie: A 750 ml bottle of beer
Tar boy: A worker who applies antiseptic tar to sheep cuts
Technicolor yawn: To vomit or spew
Tenpin bowling: United States like bowling
Throw down: A small bottle of beer you can throw down your throat quickly.
Tickets on yourself: To have a high opinion of yourself
Tim Tam: A brand of chocolate biscuits.
Tim Tam Slam: Biting off opposing corners of a Tim Tam and drinking a hot chocolate drink through it like a straw
Tinnie: A tin of beer. Also means a small aluminum boat
Tinny: Short for a small tin boat or a can of beer (both meanings apply)
Track Walker: A railway worker who inspects train tracks.
Trackie daks: Sweatpants or tracksuit pants.
True Blue Mate: A genuinely loyal Australian friend.
Turps: Turpentine. Also means alcoholic drink (i.e., On the turps!)
Two Pot Screamer: Someone who gets drunk quickly, after two drinks
Two Up: Gambling game played on Anzac Day
Ugg Boots: Sheep skin lined boots
Under the weather: Hungover or sick
Ute: A utility vehicle, like a pickup truck
Veg out: Relax or chill out.
Vegemite: A dark, salty yeast spread
Wagging school: Skipping school for the day
Waltzing Matilda: To travel or wander around, often with a swag. Inspired by the famous Australian song.
Weekend warrior: Someone who works around the house on the weekend
Whats the John Dory: Whats the Story?
Wonky: Something that is very unsteady
Wool classer: A specialist who grades and sorts wool
Wool Shed: A building where sheep are shorn.
Wowser: A very boring, extremely conservative person
XXXX: Pronounced ‘Four ex’. A beer produced in Brisbane, Queensland
Yarn: Having a conversation with someone.
Yeah nah: This essentially means that while I understand what has been said, I do not agree with it.
Yothu: Short for Yothu Yindi, a pioneering Indigenous Australian band
Your Shout: Your turn to by drinks
